lenders.name: Ellyse Lamon
lenders.occupational_info:
Ellyse Lamon has spent her whole life in the Midwest. At Fenwick High School in the Chicagoland area, she sales first entered into sales as a 15 year-old. For college, Lamon traveled north to Marquette University in Milwaukee, Wisconsin. In 2005, Ellyse Lamon graduated with a Biology degree.
Lamon has always enjoyed helping others. In high school, she joined the Children’s Memorial Guild. Lamon got friends involved and volunteered for major events. The group split into the Children’s Foundation, which Lamon still helps out with today. In 2012, Ellyse Lamon began going to regular meetings rather than just assisting with large events.
Lamon’s background led her into the medical sales field after Marquette. She worked in sales for several medical device companies in the greater Chicagoland area. At every stop, Ellyse Lamon exceeded her company’s sales goals. Lamon was known for her aggressive sales style and not taking “no” for an answer. Lamon worked for VaSol, RS Medical, Smiths Medical, Innerworkings, and Bellvue Pharmacy.
Ellyse Lamon prefers an active lifestyle in her free time. For 16 years, Lamon competed on a swim team. This likening for the water has led Lamon to enjoy scuba diving on holidays. In addition, Lamon is learning to cook. In doing this, she finds herself viewing the cooking channel in order to improve her craft. Chinese food has proved to be the most difficult to master for Lamon.
Through Dupage World Relief, Lamon took a course to teach ESL—English as a second language. In this role, Lamon gets assigned to a family and works with them for three to five months. She is currently assisting with a young student from Burma. The student has only been in the United States for seven months but is already writing short essays.
Animals are another passion of Ellyse’s. Particularly, Lamon enjoys cats. She often finds herself taking in straycats until they can find homes. Ellyse Lamon dreams of opening her own pet spa.
In September of 2013, Lamon will marry Karol Bort. Learn more about her wedding plans here

lenders.name: Michael
lenders.occupational_info:
Dr. Michael T. Garrett, Eastern Band of the Cherokee Nation, is Professor and Chair of the Department of Clinical and Professional Studies at the University of West Georgia, and is a certified school counselor.
He holds a Ph.D. in Counseling and Counselor Education and a M.Ed. in Counseling and Development from the University of North Carolina at Greensboro, and a B.A. in Psychology from North Carolina State University.

Dr. Garrett’s central research focus has emphasized exploring the relationship between cultural values, acculturation, and wellness with implications for developmental, culturally-based therapeutic interventions; strength-based work to improve wellness and resilience of children, adolescents, and adults in families, schools, and communities; better understanding bicultural competence and cultural identity development; prevention of school dropout and school academic among at-risk youth; and spiritual issues in counseling.

As author and coauthor of more than 80 professional publications dealing with multiculturalism and social justice, group work, wellness and spirituality, school counseling, working with youth, and counseling Native Americans, Dr. Garrett has also authored the books, Walking on the Wind: Cherokee Teachings for Harmony and Balance (1998), Native American Faith in America (2003, 1st ed., and 2012, 2nd ed.), and Counseling and Diversity: Counseling Native Americans (2011), and coauthored the books, Medicine of the Cherokee: The Way of Right Relationship (1996), Cherokee Full Circle: A Practical Guide to Ceremonies and Traditions (2002), and Counseling and Diversity (2012).
As a Native person who grew up on the reservation in western North Carolina where he still has strong family and community ties, Dr. Garrett’s experience with Native people, both professionally and personally, lends a unique perspective and expertise with Native American issues and concerns. Having worked as a school counselor at the middle and high school levels, as a college student personnel worker with Native American and other minority students in the university setting, as an individual and group therapist in a family services agency setting, and as a project director in an urban Native American center serving the local Native community, Dr. Garrett has sought to advance professional understanding of working with diverse populations across therapeutic and educational settings and integrating indigenous healing practices as a way of bridging the cultural gap.

lenders.name: Justin
lenders.occupational_info:
Justin David Hughes works for software maker Oracle as an account manager specializing in core technology which encompasses the Oracle Database, security, identity management, single sign-on and engineered systems. He has been in sales for over 15 years as well as the owner and operator of 2 local businesses in Maryland and Virginia. Prior to becoming employed by the software giant, Justin was in the mortgage business for 5 years as well as an account manager in internet, data and voice services.

Justin Hughes has been able to differentiate himself from other sales professionals by practicing  consultative selling, which requires for the customer’s needs to always be kept in mind. He believes in always doing right for the customer. The concept of 'consultative selling' was first published in a 1970s book Consultative Selling written by Mack Hanan, an expert in business-to-business sales. In his book, he talks about a selling technique where the salesperson positions himself as an expert to his prospect and through a series of questions uncovers the client’s needs in order to be able to sell the right product or service to meet that need. Justin Hughes echoes this by saying “If you sell your customer the right solution then they will trust you and continue to buy.”

Having graduated with a degree in Business Management from Southern Vermont College, Justin Hughes has always been drawn to a career in sales. He started his sales career as a loan officer for a mortgage company. After experiencing success within the company, Justin was asked to go to McLean, VA to run a new office with five loan officers. Once mortgage rates started escalating, he was offered a position with an internet connectivity company as an account manager and sales in internet, data and voice services. This step launched Justin’s career as a Sales Manager in the technology corridor. Justin  left his position after a few years to pursue his own entrepreneurial ventures.

After owning a furniture store and creating a painting and contracting company, Justin Hughes decided he wanted to take his experiences and go back to corporate america and technology sales. This decision is what led him to his current position at Oracle as an Account Manager. He says that Oracle is a great company to work for and he enjoys working with customers on IT solutions that help run the application environments.

lenders.name: Luisa Florez
lenders.occupational_info:
Luisa Florez is a medical examiner based in Lubbock, Texas with 5 years of experience in the field. 
Originally, Dr. Florez hails from Cali, Colombia. She completed her Doctor of Medicine at the Universidad del Cauca. In preparation for her career, Dr. Florez enrolled at the Universidad del Valle’s residency program for Pathology. Dr. Florez studied towards her specialty in clinical and anatomic pathology. While in the residency program, she was named chief resident twice. 
She then pursued her post-doctoral education as an honorary neuropathology fellow and later a pathology resident at Tulane University in New Orleans, Louisiana. 
In this capacity, Dr. Florez completed several research pieces for the university. She was a contributing author for “Tumors and Phakomatoses,” “Infectious Diseases,” “Degenerative and Demyeliinating Diseases,” as well as others. Notably, she contributed to “A Web Page to Teach Neurology and Neuropathology to Med Students” for the Wiley Online Library. 
Beginning in the year 2000, Dr. Florez began working for Louisiana State University. She worked as a Research Associate, specializing in the Genetics Division of the Department of Pediatrics. 
To round off her education, Dr. Florez completed a neuropathology fellowship at the Baylor College of Medicine in Houston, Texas. 
In 2009, she worked as an assistant medical examiner for Harris County, Texas in the Houston metropolitan area. Primarily, Dr. Florez aided in cause-of-death cases for the county. 
Throughout her career in medicine, Luisa Florez has co-produced original research that has been published in peer-reviewed journals such as the Journal of Pediatric Hematology-Oncology and Experimental Hematology. For the latter publication, she co-authored "Erythropoietin, a Hypoxia-regulated Factor, Elicits a Pro-angiogenic Program in Human Mesenchymal Stem Cells."

Heather Saucier of Houston, Texas currently works in corporate communications in the oil and gas industry. As Corporate Communications Advisor for an international oil and gas company, Heather advises management on matters such as media relations, crisis communications and public outreach strategies, in addition to writing for several of its internal and external publications. Prior to working for this company, Saucier also served as spokeswoman and manager of the communications Department and media for the Harris County Flood Control District. As Manager of the District’s Communications Department, Heather was responsible for overseeing four areas: Project Communications, Public Outreach, Internal Communications and Media. She worked with her team to develop strategies to promote the District using the media, websites, interactive application tools, public meetings and events, and collateral and promotional materials. She also ensured that all communication with the public and media was clear, consistent and effective. In addition to these responsibilities, Heather also oversaw the publication of a monthly internal newsletter for Harris District employees. As Media Manager, she proactively pitched positive stories to the media, earning approximately $2.5 million in coverage each year and also served as the District's spokeswoman for print, radio and television media.

Heather Saucier also has 16 years of experience in the journalism field, which she acquired upon graduating from the University of St. Thomas in Houston, Texas in 1995. During her time in college, Heather became a member of  the Communications Honor Society, English Honor Society, Philosophy Honor Society and Aquinas Honor Society. She graduated with honors and degrees in Communications and Philosophy. In her spare time, she enjoys running and yoga and has an interest in animal rescue.

As a management consultant in London and New York, he concentrated on leading teams during times of change such as mergers and acquisitions, strategic projects and business development. His role allowed him to engage with many clients from private equity clients to Fortune 100 firms across markets in the United States, Europe and Central Asia.
Although a native of Toronto, Canada, Ryan’s passions of learning, working and traveling have taken him to over 40 countries in the last 10 years. He is a graduate of the University of Western Ontario and holds an MBA from the London Business School and a Masters in BioMedicine from the London School of Economics and Political Science.

lenders.name: Sam W. Lee
lenders.occupational_info:
Sam W. Lee, PHD, completed his doctoral studies at the University of California-Berkeley in 1988. Following that, he worked at the University of California-San Francisco as a post-doctorate fellow. Sam W. Lee served as an assistant professor at the University of Michigan Medical School in the Division of Cancer Biology.
Sam W. Lee first worked with the Harvard College medical school in 1989 and has maintained a working relationship since then.
Most of Lee’s work has come in research. Lee has published over 100 papers. Lee’s most significant contribution came as an independent investigator in the field of p53 down stream targets involved in apoptosis and survival. He was the first to discover that pro-survival pathway activation is directly associated with p53-dependent DNA damage/geno-toxic responses in cancer cells, and have provided a unique and very significant contribution in this area.
Sam W. Lee completed Ph.D. in Molecular Genetics under Dr. Agabian at University of California. He trained as a postdoctoral fellow in the laboratories of Ruth Sager at the Dana Farber Cancer Institute/Harvard Medical School, where he began his studies on the transcriptional regulation of breast cancer genes. As an Assistant and then as an Associate Professor at the BIDMC and the MGH/Harvard Medical School, Lee pursued his major interest in how tumor suppressor p53-mediated transcriptional regulation influences cell fate decisions: live or die.
Anti-cancer therapies, including radiation and chemotherapeutic agents, ultimately eliminate tumor cells by the induction of apoptosis. However, this therapeutic opportunity is eroded by pro-survival mechanisms that inhibit apoptosis. This is expected to promote selective death of tumor cells or to sensitize tumor cells to therapy-induced apoptosis.
Sam W. Lee has been serving the NIH study section as a panel member for the last 10 years. Since 2010, Sam W. Lee has become an associate member of the Broad Institute of Harvard/MIT. His group has identified several promising small molecules with anti-cancer activity through the activation of tumor suppressor p53 apoptotic pathway. Sam W. Lee’s group now possesses considerable experience in systematic small molecule technologies. These efforts to promote awareness and usage among MGH scientists of the chemical genetics platforms established at the Broad Institute were able to bring individual investigators within the academic community closer to technological, computational and chemical biological tools that would not otherwise be accessible.

Thom Wells has led numerous public and private expeditions in scuba diving. Notably Wells helped lead the Masters Of The Arctic Expedition on behalf of the United Nations Environment Program. Wells has been a SSI Instructor Trainer, Certified Mountain Guide, Graduate of National Outdoor Leadership School as Mountain Guide PADI Master Scuba Diver Trainer, Divers Alert Network Trainer, and a Medic First Aid Instructor Trainer.
In his extensive experience, Thom Wells holds both the Platinum Pro Award for Instructor and Dive Pro in logging over 10,000 dives.
Thom Wells has worked on environmental issues and affairs that have taken him throughout the world. In over four decades of work, Wells taught hundreds of divers and dive instructors. Within the private career, he has owned wildlife and indigenous art galleries in Aspen, Colorado and Carmel California.
In his environmental work with the United Nations Environment Program, Thom Wells held the largest public art exhibition at the United Nations. This was instrumental in presenting the Global 500 Award to the Inuit people for their conservation initiatives. Thom and John Denver hosted together from the United Nations World Environment Day in 1989.
Thom Wells’ development work has included numerous condominiums, private luxury homes, and resort development in Colorado, Washington, and Hawaii. He was project manager for the Mauna Lani Resort in Hawaii. Wells also built and developed numerous luxury projects privately for many years. In this capacity, he was a broker in both Washington and Colorado states, holding the GRI designation and the Real Estate and Securities Syndication certification.
Daily, Wells works as a construction managers and design consultant through his Thomas Wells Companies, Inc. Thom Wells is fourth generation in the building business and is well known for his work with many prestigious clients and projects.
